description.plain:
“I’m Not in Love” is a cover of British band 10cc’s 1975 chart hit. The song was released as the second single from Lu’s 2019 debut album, Blood.

In 2019, “I’m Not in Love” also appeared on the Euphoria soundtrack.

description.plain: This song seems to be about Kelsey’s experience in California after having disembarked from her home and leaving behind her religious upbringing, trying instead to follow who she truly is. Finding belonging (those who are kindred), feeling unsure, and mourning are three distinct feelings you could interpret from this song.

description.plain: In this song, Kelsey describes a process of disillusionment where something that once seemed like a masterpiece is found to be fake and inauthentic. This is likely a metaphor for a person or past lover, and can be read as well as a song that details the feelings of an artist’s imposter syndrome and self-doubt.

annotations:
Bare feet against all the broken cement left untended
 Ooh-ooh-ooh, oh
 Picking the flowers of the old picket you’ve mended
 Ooh-ooh-ooh, oh

The bare feet against broken cement is acknowledging the broken and beaten path between two people, the path between them being their relationship and communication. Walking on broken cement hurts, its dangerous, and can especially hurt more when one’s feet are bare, or in this instance the rough and damaged connection between her and her parents hurts because it is in a soft and raw place, being her relationship with her parents as people she loves very dearly.

Picking the flowers on a mended fence in front of a broken sidewalk is her saying that she is trying to find the good in all of the bad, with the broken sidewalk being their broken line of communication or their damaged relationship, while the pickets represent the wall built between them being mended. For the sidewalk to be broken and the fence to be mended, it shows that the person inside the house knew they were both messed up, but still chose to only fix the fence and not the sidewalk with it.

Due west, I’m headed on this road
 Due west, just cruise as far as I can go
 To California, California, California
 Never looking back, goodbye
 A list of all the reasons why I weather through
 I do it all for you
 Ooh-ooh, oh, ooh-ooh, oh

Born and raised in Charlotte, North Carolina, Kelsey grew up Jehovah’s Witness, a devoted group of roughly 8 million Christians who proclaim the truth of Jehovah from the Bible. Despite being brought up in such a religious manner, Kelsey’s musical ambitions led her west to California to pursue her musical dream.

The chorus hears Kelsey chanting “California” three times in a style reminiscent to the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz, where the character Dorothy similarly chants “There’s no place like home” and clicks her heels three times.

https://youtu.be/LT12WuZb_DU?t=196

Didn’t know my feet were too big for my shoes
 Running in them led me to bruise
 Falling over, running home to you
 You had both my fingers and toes turning blue
 So afraid of cutting me loose
 You’re holding onto me
 You’re holding on

Kelsey uses the metaphor “my feet are too big for my shoes” to represent her curiosity and desire to explore what else life has to offer her. Her metaphorical shoes begin to bruise her, indicating that she’s stayed where she is for too long and it’s time for her to make a change.

Despite the urge for Kelsey to escape, her parents can’t bear to let her go; Kelsey compares this situation to her parents physically holding onto her so tightly that she begins to turn blue, unable to free herself. Kelsey elaborated on the song’s emotional theme of escaping and moving forward in life in a press release, saying:

[“Due West”] is a continuation of the evolution of self. A continuous questioning of the romanticism of “home” and what we leave behind in order to gain hope in what’s ahead.

Worship the ground that you walked on below your pedestal
 My mind put you onto a throne, soon enough, I’ll outgrow

As much as Kelsey wants to please her parents and do what makes them proud, she acknowledges that she is destined for a life completely different to what her parents desire.

During a 2019 interview with NPR, Kelsey reminisced on her decision to rebel against her parents' wishes, saying:

It’s important to be able to have your own narrative and to be able to have your own variation of voices

description.plain:
“Too Much” was first premiered in the music video to Kelsey’s 2018 song “Shades of Blue,” which was released almost a year prior to Blood.

The song samples Daniel Lanois' 2005 song “Carla,” over which Kelsey layers an ethereal cello and her
powerful vocals.
